	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Micheline Slattery, a human rights activist and former slave in Haiti and the United States, recalled her experiences during a forum Thursday at the University of Central Florida. Addressing an audience of nearly 300, Slattery explained how slavery is not a thing of the past, but that it exists today and occurs throughout the world.</p>
<p>Slattery began by explaining that putting young children, particularly orphans, to work as household servants, or restaveks, is a common practice in Haiti. She said the masters are often close family members of victims, as was true in her own case. Slattery was born to a prominent political family, but after being orphaned at age five was sent to live with her aunt and uncle in another town. Her father&rsquo;s sister then forced her to work in slave-like conditions.</p>
<p>Slattery was responsible for a 12-person household. She was expected to clean the house, wash and fold the laundry and walk for miles to collect water. If she failed to complete all of her chores, she was beaten with a flexible stick, similar to one used in Haitian prisons. On occasion, as punishment, her aunt forced her to kneel on a cheese grater coated with rock salt. After suffering a particularly severe beating, Slattery fled to a neighbor&rsquo;s house for help. That desperate bid actually made matters worse. When her aunt found out that Slattery had talked about her poor treatment, she struck the child across her face with a butcher knife. Slattery still bears a scar on her left cheek.</p>
<p>One day, Slattery returned home to find a woman she did not know talking with her aunt. The story the two of them told Slattery was that she would soon be reunited with her brothers and sisters in America. In fact, the stranger -- a cousin -- had bought Slattery for $2,500. After being trafficked to Connecticut where her cousin lived, Slattery resumed her life as a restavek. She recalled how she felt after learning of her selling price.</p>
<p>&ldquo;$2,500. That was all I was worth, and I began to believe it,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;All my life, those who were supposed to love me merely abused me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>While living in Connecticut, one of Slattery&rsquo;s few freedoms was to attend school. As she became exposed to life outside of forced servitude, she began to dream of running away. Eventually, at the age of 18, she stood up to her cousin&rsquo;s rule and left. She said she had &ldquo;just had enough.&rdquo;<br />
&nbsp;<br />
After escaping her life as a restavek, Slattery resettled in Massachusetts, where she works as a nurse. Recently, she began speaking out against slavery. She has testified before the Massachusetts State Assembly and has been the focus of television and print media features.&nbsp;</p>
<p>When an audience member asked if slavery is still common in Haiti, Slattery confirmed that those conditions not only continue but appear to be growing worse. Slattery&rsquo;s message was clear, &ldquo;It can&rsquo;t be a secret anymore; it&rsquo;s happening everywhere. It&rsquo;s happening here in America, in Haiti. It happened to me.&rdquo; Slattery concluded by reminding everyone in the audience that &ldquo;once you are informed that slavery still exists, you have a responsibility to speak out.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Along with the UCF Global Perspectives Office, sponsors included UCF&rsquo;s Political Science Department, UCF&rsquo;s International Services Center, UCF&rsquo;s Women's Studies Program, Lawrence J. Chastang and the Chastang Foundation, UCF LIFE and the Global Connections Foundation.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity:</strong> The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the third largest in the nation with more than 53,500 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
